@startuml Precedents Issue Architecture

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
'  Skin & Theme
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
skinparam backgroundColor #F8F9FA
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam defaultFontSize 13
skinparam roundcorner 12
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam sequenceArrowColor #37474F
skinparam sequenceLifeLineBorderColor #B0BEC5
skinparam sequenceLifeLineBackgroundColor #ECEFF1

skinparam participant {
  BackgroundColor #ECEFF1
  BorderColor #455A64
  FontStyle bold
}

skinparam actor {
  BackgroundColor #E3F2FD
  BorderColor #1565C0
}

skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #FFFDE7
  BorderColor #F9A825
  FontSize 11
}

skinparam group {
  BackgroundColor transparent
  FontStyle bold
  FontSize 12
}

title Coordinator-Managed Parallel Subagent Architecture\nReducing Legal Precedent Analysis Latency

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
'  Participants
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
actor       "User / System"           as U    #E3F2FD
participant "Coordinator"             as CO   #E8EAF6
participant "DocAgent-1\n(P1–P4)"     as DA1  #E0F7FA
participant "DocAgent-2\n(P5–P8)"     as DA2  #E0F7FA
participant "DocAgent-3\n(P9–P12)"    as DA3  #E0F7FA
participant "Aggregator"              as AG   #FFF3E0
participant "Synthesis Agent"         as SA   #F3E5F5

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
'  PART 1 — THE PROBLEM (Sequential)
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
== ❌ BEFORE — Sequential Processing (3+ minutes) ==

U  ->  CO  : analyze landmark case\n(12 precedents)

note over CO
  Single DocAgent processes
  P1 → P2 → P3 → … → P12
  one at a time — no parallelism.
end note

CO -> DA1 : analyze P1
DA1 --> CO : result P1  [~15s]
CO -> DA1 : analyze P2
DA1 --> CO : result P2  [~15s]
CO -> DA1 : analyze P3..P12
DA1 --> CO : results P3–P12  [~150s]

note over CO, DA1
  Total wall-clock time ≈ 12 × 15s = 180s (3 min+)
  Coordinator is blocked waiting.
  No parallelism. No observability during processing.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
'  PART 2 — CORRECT ANSWER (Coordinator Parallel Fan-Out)
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
== ✅ AFTER — Coordinator-Managed Parallel Fan-Out (Option C) ==

U  ->  CO  : analyze landmark case\n(12 precedents)

CO -> CO : partition precedents into\n3 subsets of 4

note over CO
  Coordinator owns the fan-out plan.
  It decides subset size, spawn count,
  assigns work, and holds full visibility
  into every spawned subagent.
end note

CO ->  DA1 : spawn + assign(P1, P2, P3, P4)
CO ->  DA2 : spawn + assign(P5, P6, P7, P8)
CO ->  DA3 : spawn + assign(P9, P10, P11, P12)

note over CO
  All three subagents run in parallel.
  Coordinator polls / awaits all three
  simultaneously — not sequentially.
end note

group Parallel Execution (~15s wall-clock)
  DA1 -> DA1 : analyze P1→P4
  DA2 -> DA2 : analyze P5→P8
  DA3 -> DA3 : analyze P9→P12
end

DA1 --> CO : AnalysisResult{P1..P4, citations[], findings[]}
DA2 --> CO : AnalysisResult{P5..P8, citations[], findings[]}
DA3 --> CO : AnalysisResult{P9..P12, citations[], findings[]}

note over CO
  Wall-clock time ≈ 15s
  (cost of one subset, not 12 sequential precedents)
  Coordinator received structured results from all agents.
end note

CO ->  AG  : aggregate([Result_DA1, Result_DA2, Result_DA3])

note right of AG
  Aggregation responsibilities:
  • Merge findings[] across all subsets
  • Deduplicate overlapping citations
  • Resolve conflicts (flag contradictions)
  • Validate citation coverage per precedent
  • Produce unified AnalysisBundle
end note

AG --> CO : AnalysisBundle (all 12 precedents)
CO ->  SA  : synthesize(AnalysisBundle)
SA --> CO  : final legal analysis report
CO -->  U  : ✅ Final Report (~15–20s total)

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
'  PART 3 — WHY THE OTHER OPTIONS FAIL
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
== ❌ Option A — Recursive Agent Hierarchy ==

note across
  Option A: Recursive Agent Hierarchy — Why It Fails
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Coordinator
    └─ AnalysisAgent
         ├─ SubAgent (P1–P6)
         │    ├─ ChildAgent (P1–P3)
         │    │    ├─ LeafAgent (P1)
         │    │    └─ LeafAgent (P2–P3)
         │    └─ ChildAgent (P4–P6) → ...
         └─ SubAgent (P7–P12) → ...

  PROBLEMS:
  ❌ Debug/monitoring: Coordinator cannot see into nested layers directly.
     A failure at LeafAgent(P1) is invisible until it bubbles up multiple hops.
  ❌ Latency: Recursion adds spawn-and-wait overhead at every layer.
     No real speedup beyond the first fan-out — same wall-clock as flat parallelism
     but with extra coordination cost.
  ❌ Error propagation: A crash in a mid-level node orphans entire subtrees.
  ❌ Complexity: Dynamic tree depth makes the execution graph non-deterministic.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
== ❌ Option B — External Message Queue ==

note across
  Option B: Message Queue with Worker Agents — Why It Fails
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Coordinator → Queue → [Worker1, Worker2, Worker3, ...]

  PROBLEMS:
  ❌ Observability: Coordinator pushes tasks to the queue and loses direct
     awareness of which worker picked up which task.
  ❌ Aggregation timing: Coordinator must poll or subscribe to know when
     ALL 12 precedents are done — hard to correlate results to tasks.
  ❌ Debugging: A failed task sits in a dead-letter queue; the coordinator
     has no structured AnalysisResult to inspect, only an absence.
  ❌ Added infrastructure: Requires external broker (Kafka, SQS, etc.),
     adding failure modes and operational overhead outside the agent system.
  ❌ Violates single-hub principle: Monitoring is split between the
     coordinator and the queue dashboard — no single source of truth.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
== ❌ Option D — Subagent Self-Spawning (User's Pick) ==

note across
  Option D: DocAgent Spawns Its Own Subagents Dynamically — Why It Fails
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Coordinator
    └─ DocAgent
         ├─ (dynamically spawns) SpecializedAgent(P1)
         ├─ (dynamically spawns) SpecializedAgent(P2)
         └─ ... (dynamic, coordinator cannot predict or observe)

  PROBLEMS:
  ❌ Hidden execution: Coordinator spawned ONE DocAgent.
     It does not know DocAgent internally spun up 12 children.
     From the coordinator's view: one black box, unknown state.
  ❌ Monitoring gap: If SpecializedAgent(P7) fails, the coordinator
     sees only a delayed or missing DocAgent result — no granularity.
  ❌ Debug incompleteness: Stack traces, partial results, and logs
     are buried inside DocAgent — coordinator's debug view is incomplete.
  ❌ Resource control: Coordinator cannot set parallelism limits or
     prioritize subsets — DocAgent self-determines load.
  ❌ No aggregation hub: Each dynamic child's output is stitched inside
     DocAgent, not at a neutral aggregation layer the coordinator controls.
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  This is the user's chosen answer. It achieves parallelism but sacrifices
  the coordinator's ability to monitor, debug, and control execution —
  the exact requirement stated in the problem.
end note

' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
'  PART 4 — COMPARATIVE SUMMARY
' ─────────────────────────────────────────────
== Summary: Why Option C Wins on All Three Axes ==

note across
  Evaluation Matrix
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  │ Criterion                  │  A (Recursive) │  B (Queue)  │  C (Coordinator ✅) │  D (Self-Spawn) │
  ├────────────────────────────┼────────────────┼─────────────┼─────────────────────┼─────────────────┤
  │ Latency reduction          │  Partial       │  Yes        │  ✅ Yes              │  Yes            │
  │ Coordinator monitoring     │  ❌ Broken     │  ❌ Broken  │  ✅ Full visibility  │  ❌ Broken      │
  │ Coordinator debug view     │  ❌ Indirect   │  ❌ Absent  │  ✅ Direct results   │  ❌ Incomplete  │
  │ Single aggregation hub     │  ❌ Scattered  │  ❌ Queue   │  ✅ Coordinator owns │  ❌ DocAgent    │
  │ Scope tight per subagent   │  Variable      │  Per task   │  ✅ Fixed subset     │  Dynamic        │
  │ Error containment          │  ❌ Tree-wide  │  ❌ DLQ     │  ✅ Per-subagent     │  ❌ Hidden      │
  │ Implementation simplicity  │  ❌ Complex    │  ❌ Infra   │  ✅ Simple fan-out   │  Moderate       │
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Option C is the ONLY design that simultaneously reduces latency AND
  preserves the coordinator as a single, trusted hub for spawning,
  monitoring, aggregation, and debugging.
end note

@enduml